      "inline_content": "Version: 1.0 Date: November 15, 2025 Document Type: Product Vision & Technical Specification Purpose: Vision document for GiljoAI MCP product creation and chunk testing TinyContacts is a streamlined, modern contact management application designed to provide individuals and small teams with an elegant, distraction-free solution for organizing their professional and personal networks. In an era where contact information is scattered across multiple platforms, email clients, social media networks, and handwritten notes, TinyContacts offers a unified, centralized repository that puts you back in control of your connections. The application embodies the philosophy of \"simplicity without sacrifice\" - delivering essential contact management features without the bloat and complexity that plague enterprise CRM systems. TinyContacts is intentionally designed as a lightweight, focused tool that does one thing exceptionally well: helping you maintain and organize contact information efficiently. At its core, TinyContacts enables users to store comprehensive contact profiles including names, email addresses, phone numbers, profile photos, and important dates such as birthdays, anniversaries, and custom milestones. The application features an intuitive single-page interface with modal-based editing, ensuring users can add, update, search, and manage contacts with minimal cognitive load and maximum efficiency. The product vision extends beyond basic CRUD operations. TinyContacts is built on modern web technologies that ensure fast performance, responsive design across devices, and a user experience that feels native and fluid. Whether accessing the application from a desktop workstation, tablet, or mobile device, users experience the same consistent, polished interface optimized for their screen size and interaction patterns. TinyContacts represents a strategic departure from bloated contact management solutions. It eschews unnecessary features like complex workflow automation, AI-powered relationship scoring, or elaborate social media integrations in favor of rock-solid reliability, blazing-fast performance, and an interface so intuitive that users require zero training. The application is designed to be immediately useful from the moment of first launch, with sensible defaults and an empty-state experience that guides users toward their first successful contact creation. The architecture of TinyContacts emphasizes developer-friendly patterns and maintainable code. Built with modern Python FastAPI backend and React TypeScript frontend, the codebase is clean, well-documented, and structured for easy extension. This makes TinyContacts an ideal candidate for demonstrating the capabilities of the GiljoAI MCP orchestration system, where specialized agents can collaborate on distinct features, modules, and layers of the application architecture. From a business perspective, TinyContacts occupies a unique market position. While enterprise solutions like Salesforce, HubSpot, and Microsoft Dynamics dominate the high-end CRM market, and basic address books ship with operating systems and email clients, there exists a significant gap for individuals and small teams who need more than a simple address book but less than a full CRM platform. TinyContacts fills this gap perfectly, offering professional-grade contact management without enterprise complexity or pricing. The target user persona for TinyContacts includes freelancers, consultants, small business owners, researchers, writers, event organizers, and anyone who maintains a professional network but doesn't require (or want) the overhead of enterprise software. These users value their time, appreciate clean design, and want tools that enhance their productivity rather than demanding extensive configuration and learning curves. Security and privacy are foundational considerations in TinyContacts design. The application stores all contact data locally by default, ensuring users maintain complete ownership and control of their information. There are no third-party trackers, no analytics beacons, and no cloud synchronization unless explicitly configured. This privacy-first approach resonates with users increasingly concerned about data sovereignty and the commercialization of personal information. The development roadmap for TinyContacts includes several planned enhancement phases. Version 1.0 focuses on core contact management with a single-user model. Version 2.0 will introduce optional authentication and multi-user support, enabling small teams to share contact databases. Version 3.0 plans to add import/export capabilities for vCard and CSV formats, enabling migration from other contact management tools. Future versions may explore optional cloud synchronization, mobile native applications, and browser extensions for capturing contact information from web pages and email signatures. Performance benchmarks for TinyContacts target sub-100ms response times for all API operations, sub-second contact search across databases of 10,000+ contacts, and instantaneous UI updates leveraging optimistic rendering patterns. The application is designed to remain responsive and snappy even as contact databases grow, utilizing efficient database indexing, pagination strategies, and intelligent caching. Accessibility is a core design principle, with TinyContacts adhering to WCAG 2.1 Level AA standards. The interface is fully keyboard-navigable, screen reader compatible, and designed with sufficient color contrast and scalable typography. Form validation provides clear, actionable error messages, and all interactive elements feature appropriate ARIA labels and roles. The backend API maintains >85% code coverage with pytest, while frontend components are validated with React Testing Library and Cypress for E2E workflows. This robust testing foundation ensures confidence during refactoring and feature additions, supporting the rapid iteration cycles that characterize modern software development. Documentation for TinyContacts includes user guides, API reference documentation, developer setup instructions, and architectural decision records (ADRs) that explain key design choices. This comprehensive documentation serves both end users seeking to maximize their productivity and developers looking to understand, extend, or integrate with the application. From a deployment perspective, TinyContacts supports multiple installation methods. Users can run the application locally via simple Python and Node.js commands, deploy to container platforms like Docker, or host on cloud platforms such as AWS, Google Cloud, or Azure. The application's modest resource requirements mean it runs comfortably on minimal infrastructure, reducing hosting costs and environmental impact. The TinyContacts user interface leverages modern design patterns including card- based layouts, modal dialogs, contextual menus, and responsive grid systems. Visual feedback accompanies all user actions through subtle animations, loading states, and success confirmations. The color palette is carefully chosen to be both aesthetically pleasing and functional, with distinct colors for different action types (create, update, delete) and clear visual hierarchy guiding user attention. Search functionality in TinyContacts goes beyond simple string matching. The application implements fuzzy search algorithms that tolerate typos and partial matches, enabling users to quickly locate contacts even with imperfect recall. Search results highlight matching terms, and the interface provides filtering options to narrow results by criteria such as contacts with upcoming birthdays, recent additions, or contacts lacking certain information fields. Data validation in TinyContacts strikes a balance between strictness and flexibility. Email addresses are validated against RFC standards but accept international characters and new TLDs. This validation approach prevents obvious errors while accommodating the diversity of real-world contact information. Photo management in TinyContacts includes automatic image optimization, generating appropriately sized thumbnails and display versions from uploaded originals. The system accepts common image formats (JPEG, PNG, GIF, WebP) and applies sensible file size limits to prevent storage bloat. Users can easily update or remove contact photos, with the interface providing instant visual feedback during upload operations. Beyond typical birthdays and anniversaries, users can define custom date types such as \"First Meeting,\" \"Contract Renewal,\" \"Project Deadline,\" or any other milestone worth remembering. The interface supports adding, editing, and removing dates inline, with date picker controls that work seamlessly across desktop and mobile browsers. TinyContacts employs progressive enhancement principles, ensuring core functionality works even in degraded network conditions or older browsers. JavaScript enhancements provide the optimal experience, but the application remains usable with basic HTML form submissions as a fallback. The error handling philosophy in TinyContacts prioritizes user clarity and recovery. When errors occur, users receive plain-language explanations of what went wrong and actionable steps to resolve the issue. Technical error details are logged for developer diagnosis but hidden from end users unless debugging mode is enabled. Network failures trigger automatic retry logic with exponential backoff, preventing transient connectivity issues from disrupting workflows. Internationalization support is planned for future TinyContacts releases, with the architecture designed to accommodate multiple languages and locales. String literals are externalized into resource files, date and number formatting respects user locale preferences, and the UI layout accommodates languages with different text directionality (RTL support). The analytics and telemetry approach in TinyContacts is opt-in and transparent. Users must explicitly enable usage analytics, and can review exactly what data is collected before granting permission. The analytics system operates independently from core functionality, ensuring privacy-conscious users receive full product value without data sharing. Community and ecosystem considerations position TinyContacts as an open, extensible platform. The application exposes well-documented APIs that enable third-party integrations, extensions, and complementary tools. A planned plugin architecture will allow developers to extend functionality without modifying core code, fostering a community of contributors who can customize the application to specialized needs. From a technical debt perspective, TinyContacts prioritizes sustainable development practices. The codebase follows consistent style guides enforced by automated linting, includes comprehensive inline documentation, and undergoes regular refactoring to prevent architectural erosion. Dependency management is active, with regular updates to address security vulnerabilities and leverage improvements in underlying libraries and frameworks. The competitive analysis reveals that TinyContacts differentiates through simplicity, speed, and privacy. While competitors offer more features, they often overwhelm users with complexity and raise privacy concerns through aggressive data collection. TinyContacts competes on doing the essentials exceptionally well, loading instantly, respecting user privacy, and never getting in the way of actual work. Use these snippets to quickly populate the product creation form in GiljoAI MCP: {Description (Context for Orchestrator)} Modern contact management application for individuals and small teams. Streamlined CRUD interface for managing contacts with photos, emails, phone numbers, and important dates. Single-page React app with FastAPI backend, featuring instant search, modal-based editing, and local-first architecture. Target users: freelancers, consultants, small business owners. Key features: photo uploads with automatic optimization, important dates tracking (birthdays, anniversaries), tag-based organization, fuzzy search, export capabilities. Privacy-first design with local SQLite storage (PostgreSQL for teams). {Frontend Frameworks & Libraries} React 18.2+ TypeScript 5.0+ Vite 5.0+ (build tooling) Tailwind CSS 3.3+ (styling) TanStack Query 5.0+ (data fetching) React Hook Form 7.45+ (form management) React Router 6+ (routing) {Backend Frameworks & Services} FastAPI 0.104+ SQLAlchemy 2.0+ (ORM) SQLModel (Pydantic integration) Alembic (migrations) Uvicorn 0.23+ (ASGI server) Pillow 10.0+ (image processing) Pydantic 2.0+ (validation) {Infrastructure & DevOps} Docker + Docker Compose (containerization) Uvicorn/Gunicorn (ASGI production server) Nginx (reverse proxy, optional) GitHub Actions (CI/CD) Systemd services (Linux deployment) {Primary Architecture Pattern} Modular monolith with service layer separation. Backend organized into distinct service modules (ProductService, ProjectService, OrchestrationService) with clear boundaries and responsibilities. MVC-inspired separation with FastAPI routers (controllers), service layer (business logic), and SQLAlchemy models (data). {API Style and Communication} REST API (primary interface, JSON payloads) OpenAPI 3.0 (automatic documentation via FastAPI) WebSocket (real-time updates for multi-user scenarios, planned v2.0) Multipart/form-data (photo uploads) Server-Sent Events (optional for live updates) HTTP/2 support (via modern ASGI servers) CORS configuration (cross-origin support for SPA) Progressive enhancement from single-user to multi-tenant without major refactoring. Database migrations managed via Alembic with version control. API versioning strategy: URL-based (/api/v1/) when breaking changes required. Security: input validation via Pydantic, parameterized queries prevent SQL injection, CSRF protection for multi-user deployments. {Core Features} Contact Management: Create, read, update, delete contacts with name, email, phone, photo, and custom notes. Photo uploads with automatic resizing and optimization (thumbnail, card, full-size variants). Tag-based organization for categorizing contacts (clients, friends, family, conference attendees, etc.). Single-page interface with modal-based editing for zero-navigation workflow. Data export: vCard and CSV formats for portability (v2.0). Import contacts from CSV, vCard, email signatures (v2.0). Responsive design: mobile, tablet, desktop optimized. Accessibility: WCAG 2.1 Level AA compliance, keyboard navigation, screen reader support. {Testing Strategy and Approach} Hybrid approach (combination of TDD for critical paths, integration testing for workflows, E2E for user journeys) NOTE: Select \"Hybrid approach\" from the dropdown menu The selection of Python 3.11+ as the primary backend language reflects several strategic considerations. Python's ecosystem provides mature, battle-tested libraries for web development, database interaction, and image processing. Python 3.11 introduces significant performance improvements over earlier versions, with benchmarks showing 10-60% faster execution for typical web application workloads. Type hints and modern Python features like match statements, exception groups, and enhanced error messages contribute to more robust, self-documenting code. The Python runtime's cross-platform compatibility ensures TinyContacts deploys consistently across Windows, macOS, and Linux environments without platform- specific code branches. Package management via pip and virtual environments provides isolated, reproducible dependency installation that prevents version conflicts and simplifies deployment. From a developer productivity standpoint, Python's extensive standard library reduces the need for third-party dependencies for common tasks like datetime manipulation, file I/O, regular expressions, and JSON processing. This minimizes the application's dependency footprint and reduces supply chain security risks. The Python community's strong emphasis on testing, documentation, and code quality aligns perfectly with TinyContacts' engineering values. Tools like pytest, black, ruff, and mypy integrate seamlessly into development workflows, enforcing consistency and catching bugs before they reach production. FastAPI serves as the backbone of TinyContacts' REST API layer, chosen for its modern design, exceptional performance, and developer-friendly features. Built on Starlette and Pydantic, FastAPI delivers async request handling that outperforms traditional synchronous Python web frameworks by significant margins in benchmarks. The framework's dependency injection system enables clean separation of concerns, making route handlers focused and testable. Type hints drive automatic request validation and response serialization, eliminating boilerplate code while providing excellent IDE autocomplete support. FastAPI's async capabilities enable efficient handling of I/O-bound operations like database queries and file uploads without blocking the event loop. This concurrency model allows TinyContacts to serve multiple requests simultaneously on modest hardware, improving responsiveness under load. The framework's middleware system provides elegant solutions for cross-cutting concerns like CORS, request logging, error handling, and performance monitoring. Built-in support for modern authentication patterns (OAuth2, JWT) positions the application for future multi-user features. FastAPI's active development community, comprehensive documentation, and growing adoption in production environments provide confidence in the framework's longevity and support. Regular updates deliver performance improvements, security patches, and new features without breaking existing code. The dual database strategy reflects TinyContacts' progressive deployment model. SQLite serves as the default database for single-user installations, offering zero-configuration setup, serverless architecture, and file-based storage that simplifies backups and migrations. SQLite's reliability (tested to 100% branch coverage) and broad platform support make it ideal for desktop and personal use cases. SQLite's performance characteristics suit contact management workloads exceptionally well. The database handles thousands of contacts with sub- millisecond query times, especially when proper indexes cover search and filter operations. For team deployments and scenarios requiring concurrent multi-user access, PostgreSQL provides enterprise-grade reliability, ACID compliance, and advanced features like JSON columns for flexible schema evolution. PostgreSQL's mature replication and backup solutions support high-availability deployments. The application's data access layer abstracts database-specific details through SQLAlchemy ORM, enabling seamless switching between SQLite and PostgreSQL via configuration changes. Database migrations are managed through Alembic, providing version-controlled schema evolution and safe production upgrades. Both databases support the application's data model efficiently, with foreign key constraints ensuring referential integrity, indexes optimizing common query patterns, and transactions maintaining consistency during concurrent operations. SQLAlchemy 2.0 represents a major evolution in Python's premier database toolkit, introducing modern async support, improved type hinting, and more intuitive APIs. The framework's powerful ORM abstracts database specifics while providing escape hatches for raw SQL when needed. SQLModel bridges SQLAlchemy and Pydantic, enabling database models that double as API schemas. This reduces code duplication and ensures consistency between database layer and API contracts. Models define validation rules once, applied both during database writes and API request handling. The ORM's relationship loading strategies (lazy, eager, subquery) enable optimization of N+1 query problems common in contact management scenarios. Selective eager loading fetches contact photos and important dates efficiently, minimizing database round-trips. SQLAlchemy's migration tooling (Alembic) generates schema migrations automatically from model changes, maintaining a version history that supports safe rollbacks and audit trails. Database schema evolution becomes a controlled, reviewable process rather than risky manual alterations. The framework's extensive configuration options tune behavior for specific deployment contexts. React provides the foundation for TinyContacts' user interface, chosen for its component-based architecture, virtual DOM performance, and massive ecosystem. The library's maturity and widespread adoption ensure long-term support, abundant learning resources, and a steady stream of community contributions. React 18's concurrent rendering features enable smoother user experiences during intensive operations like searching large contact lists or rendering contact grids. Automatic batching reduces unnecessary re-renders, improving responsiveness. Transitions API provides fine-grained control over loading states and progressive enhancement of content. TypeScript integration adds static type checking to JavaScript, catching errors during development rather than runtime. Type definitions for props, state, and function signatures serve as living documentation and enable intelligent IDE autocomplete. The compiler's strictness prevents common bugs like null reference errors, undefined property access, and type mismatches. Custom hooks encapsulate reusable logic for API calls, form handling, and local storage synchronization, promoting DRY principles and testability. These libraries integrate seamlessly, providing battle-tested patterns for common SPA challenges. React's component model encourages UI decomposition into small, focused, reusable pieces. ContactCard, ContactForm, DatesEditor, and SearchBar components each handle specific responsibilities, tested in isolation and composed into complete features. This modularity simplifies reasoning about UI behavior and accelerates feature development. Vite revolutionizes the frontend development experience with near-instantaneous server startup and lightning-fast hot module replacement. Unlike traditional bundlers that rebuild entire applications on code changes, Vite leverages native ES modules in development for instant updates that preserve application state. The build tool's production bundling utilizes Rollup under the hood, generating optimized bundles with code splitting, tree shaking, and asset optimization. Chunk splitting strategies ensure common dependencies load once across routes, minimizing payload sizes and accelerating page loads. Vite's plugin ecosystem provides seamless integration with TypeScript, React, CSS preprocessors, and various asset types. Configuration remains minimal for standard setups while exposing extensive customization for advanced needs. The tool's sensible defaults handle most scenarios without configuration, embodying zero-config philosophy. API requests route through Vite's dev server to the backend, simplifying the development environment setup. This rapid feedback cycle supports iterative development and makes comprehensive rebuilds practical within continuous integration pipelines. Tailwind CSS provides utility-first styling that accelerates UI development without sacrificing customization. The framework's comprehensive utility classes cover spacing, typography, colors, layout, and responsive design, enabling developers to style components without leaving HTML/JSX. The JIT (Just-In-Time) compiler generates only the CSS classes actually used in the application, producing minimal stylesheets regardless of Tailwind's full feature set. This eliminates concerns about framework bloat and delivers tiny CSS bundles that load instantly. Responsive design becomes trivial with Tailwind's breakpoint prefixes. The same component adapts to mobile, tablet, and desktop layouts through variant classes like 'md:grid-cols-2' and 'lg:grid-cols-4'. This consistency in responsive patterns accelerates development and reduces bugs. Customization happens through configuration, defining color palettes, spacing scales, and design tokens that propagate throughout the application. This ensures visual consistency and makes global design updates trivial - change a value in the config, and all usages update automatically. The 'dark:' prefix applies styles conditionally based on system preferences or manual toggles, providing accessible options for different lighting conditions and user preferences. The utility-first approach eliminates decision paralysis around class naming conventions and CSS architecture patterns. Developers focus on implementing designs rather than debating BEM, OOCSS, or SMACSS methodologies. TanStack Query revolutionizes data fetching in React applications through powerful caching, background refetching, and optimistic updates. Automatic background refetching keeps contact data fresh without user intervention. Stale data refetches when users focus the application or reconnect after network interruptions, ensuring they always see current information. Configurable stale times balance freshness with API efficiency. Query invalidation provides granular control over cache updates. When a contact is updated, related queries invalidate automatically, triggering refetches that propagate changes throughout the UI. This maintains consistency without manual state synchronization logic. Optimistic updates enhance perceived performance by immediately reflecting changes in the UI before server confirmation. The library manages rollback if API calls fail, preserving consistency without sacrificing responsiveness. Users experience instant feedback that creates a native-app feel. The library's DevTools provide visibility into query states, cache contents, and fetch timings during development. This observability accelerates debugging and optimization, revealing inefficient fetch patterns and caching opportunities. Built-in support for pagination, infinite scrolling, and parallel queries handles common data fetching patterns with minimal code. Mutations abstract API calls that modify data, integrating with query invalidation to maintain cache consistency. The library leverages uncontrolled components and refs to minimize React's re-rendering overhead, making complex forms with many fields responsive and smooth. Email, phone, and required field validations are defined once and applied consistently across create and edit forms. The library's register function connects form inputs with minimal boilerplate, eliminating the controlled component ceremony of value/onChange props. Validation triggers on blur, change, or submit events based on configuration, balancing immediate feedback with avoiding premature error messages. Form state management through useForm hook provides access to dirty fields, touched inputs, validation errors, and submission status. Field array support handles the dynamic important dates list elegantly. Users add, remove, and reorder date entries with the library managing array state and validation. This pattern extends to any variable-length form sections without complex state management. TypeScript integration provides strong typing for form data, ensuring type safety from form submission through API calls to database storage. The compiler catches schema mismatches that could cause runtime errors or data corruption. Pillow handles server-side image processing for contact photos, providing resize, crop, and format conversion capabilities. Uploaded images are automatically resized to appropriate dimensions for display, reducing storage requirements and accelerating page loads. Multiple size variants generate from each upload - thumbnail, card, and full- size versions serve different UI contexts optimally. The srcset attribute in image tags enables browsers to select appropriate variants based on display density and viewport size. JPEG for photos and PNG for graphics with transparency ensures efficient file sizes without quality degradation. Modern format support (WebP, AVIF) provides additional optimization for capable browsers through progressive enhancement. Image validation prevents malformed files from entering the system. File type verification, dimension checks, and size limits protect against excessively large uploads or potentially malicious files. The library's robust error handling gracefully rejects invalid uploads with clear user feedback. Thumbnail generation leverages efficient algorithms that balance quality and performance. Lanczos resampling produces sharp thumbnails from larger images without artifacts, maintaining professional appearance at all sizes. Contact photos store in a dedicated uploads directory with organized subdirectories by year/month for scalability. This structure prevents single directories from containing excessive files, which can degrade filesystem performance. File naming strategies use unique identifiers to prevent collisions and enable safe concurrent uploads. UUIDs or sequential IDs combined with original extensions create filenames that are URL-safe, unique, and recognizable. The storage layer abstracts file operations behind an interface, enabling future migration to cloud storage (S3, GCS, Azure Blob) without changing business logic. This abstraction separates storage concerns from core application code. Backup strategies leverage the filesystem's simplicity - standard file backup tools handle photo archives without special considerations. The uploads directory copies independently of database backups, or together in complete system snapshots. File cleanup processes remove orphaned images when contacts are deleted, preventing storage bloat. Background tasks or deletion hooks ensure the filesystem and database remain synchronized, avoiding dead references. Uvicorn serves as the ASGI server running the FastAPI application, chosen for its performance, standards compliance, and production readiness. The server's async architecture handles concurrent requests efficiently, critical for responsive APIs. Hot reload during development accelerates iteration cycles, automatically restarting the server when code changes. This eliminates manual server restarts and maintains rapid feedback loops during feature development. The server's logging capabilities provide visibility into requests, responses, and errors. Worker process management allows scaling the application across multiple CPU cores. Gunicorn or similar process managers can spawn multiple Uvicorn workers, distributing load across available hardware for improved throughput. SSL/TLS support enables HTTPS in development and production, securing data in transit. HTTPX provides a test client that makes requests to the FastAPI application without network calls. This enables fast, reliable API integration tests that verify endpoint behavior, validation rules, and error handling in isolation. Component tests verify rendering, user interactions, and state changes in isolation from the backend. React Testing Library encourages testing components from a user perspective, querying elements by accessible attributes rather than implementation details. This produces tests that remain stable during refactoring and accurately reflect user experience. Cypress end-to-end tests validate complete user workflows, from opening the application through creating, editing, searching, and deleting contacts. These tests provide confidence that integrated components work together correctly. Coverage reports integrate into CI pipelines, failing builds that drop below configured thresholds. The same mock definitions serve development and testing, ensuring consistency and reducing setup overhead. Backend: Ruff (linting) + Black (formatting) Frontend: ESLint + Prettier Ruff provides extremely fast Python linting, checking code 